📄 Project Overview
🚀 Resilient and Scalable Web Application Deployment on AWS

This project was designed and implemented to build a highly available, scalable, and secure web application infrastructure on Amazon Web Services (AWS).

The primary objective of this project was to address real-world challenges such as handling variable traffic loads, ensuring minimal downtime, and maintaining data persistence across multiple instances.

🎯 Why This Project Was Built

In modern cloud environments, applications must be able to:

Handle increasing user traffic without performance degradation

Remain available even if some components fail

Scale automatically based on demand

Ensure secure communication between services

This project was created to simulate a production-ready cloud architecture that solves these challenges using AWS services.

🧠 Problem Statement

Traditional single-server architectures suffer from:

Single point of failure

Limited scalability

Data inconsistency across instances

Manual intervention during traffic spikes

To overcome these limitations, a distributed and automated architecture was required.

🏗️ Solution Overview

To solve these challenges, a multi-tier AWS architecture was implemented using:

Amazon EC2 → Hosts the web application

Amazon EFS → Provides shared and persistent storage

Elastic Load Balancing → Distributes incoming traffic across instances

AWS Auto Scaling → Automatically adjusts the number of instances based on demand

VPC → Provides isolated and secure network environment

⚙️ Key Features
🔹 High Availability

Deployed resources across multiple Availability Zones

Load Balancer ensures traffic distribution

Auto Scaling replaces failed instances automatically

🔹 Scalability

Auto Scaling dynamically increases or decreases EC2 instances

System handles traffic spikes without manual intervention

🔹 Data Persistence

EFS provides shared storage across all EC2 instances

Data remains intact even if instances are terminated

🔹 Security

Implemented Security Group chaining:

ALB → EC2 → EFS

EC2 instances are not directly exposed to the internet

Controlled and secure communication between services

🔹 Fault Tolerance

If one instance fails, traffic is routed to healthy instances

Auto Scaling launches new instances automatically

🎯 Outcome

The final architecture successfully achieved:

Seamless traffic distribution

Automatic scaling based on demand

Secure and isolated infrastructure

High availability with minimal downtime

Persistent shared storage across instances

💡 Conclusion

This project demonstrates how AWS services can be combined to build a robust, production-ready cloud architecture capable of handling real-world application requirements such as scalability, availability, and security.
